Use ASP.NET Core's `WebApplicationFactory<T>` from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It spins up your full middleware pipeline in-memory — no real port, no network.

**Setup:**

```csharp
// Install: Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing

public class McpServerTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpServerTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var client = _factory.CreateClient();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonDocument>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.RootElement.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion").GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        var client = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Initialize first, then call tool
        await InitializeSession(client);

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my_tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        // Assert on result content...
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

1. **No real server** — `CreateClient()` gives you an `HttpClient` wired to the in-memory test host
2. **Full pipeline** — middleware, DI, routing all run as in production
3. **Mock dependencies** — override services via `WithWebHostBuilder`:

```csharp
var factory = _factory.WithWebHostBuilder(builder =>
{
    builder.ConfigureServices(services =>
    {
        services.AddSingleton<IMyService, FakeMyService>();
    });
});
```

4. **SSE streaming** — for Streamable HTTP, read the response stream incrementally:

```csharp
var response = await client.SendAsync(request,
    HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);
using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);
// Read SSE events line by line
```

This gives you true integration coverage of the MCP JSON-RPC protocol without any external process or port allocation.
